segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I'm interviewing Mr. Franklin Sequeira on the history of Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 13, 1984.
I've already given a little introductory, but I'd like for you to tell me what your background is.
Okay.
Well, my background has basically been in new business ventures and private industry.
I guess ever since I got out of college I've been interested in business start-ups, and I've been involved in a number of them under the umbrella of major corporations.

So I was manager of special projects at North American Aviation in Columbus, Ohio, where we did some work in setting up joint ventures on commercial aircraft, even though this was a military aircraft main venture.
some joint maintenance work with another aircraft firm, or aircraft leasing firm, some manufacturing ventures.
And I left North American Aviation in 1970, went to Continental Can Company, as it was known as in those days, as head of research and engineering planning for the can company.
And there we were looking at new packaging ventures,
I had about 30 people working for me, about half of them were planners, the other half were administrators and typewriters.
From there I went to Can Company headquarters as the Can Company director of new business ventures and we set up some venture capital operations.
From that to the corporate office in New York as corporate manager of acquisitions and mergers.
I'm the corporate general manager of technology and venture operations, and I'm finally vice president and general manager of a startup.
So I've been involved in high-tech business startup operations probably most of my business life.
How did Taze come to know about you?
Oh, well, I answered a Wall Street Journal ad.
It sounded like something that was just tailored to what I wanted to do.
After 12 years at Continental, they decided that they were going to stick more to existing businesses rather than creating new ones.
And the past five years have been very exciting.
We were involved in developing new high-energy density batteries, new pharmaceuticals.
We got an anti-addictive drug that we were taking through FDA approval.
This would be allowing an alcoholic to detoxify without trauma.
It seemed to have anti-heron and anti-nicotine properties.
We had a topical cure for herpes 2.
At least that's the way it was testing out in the laboratory.
It hadn't gone to human tests or anything.
And the company I started at Continental was called Continental Power Systems Incorporated.
And that was a company that had licensed a new form of electrical generator and variable speed AC motor.
And we were starting that up.
got a new chairman of the board.
He said, well, we're going to make cans and punch holes in the Gulf of Mexico.
And I saw the ads and said, wow.
Looks better in Texas than it does in Connecticut.
Was this your first venture in Texas?
Well, we were running the pharmaceutical venture down in Houston.
We had a
program office down there, and if you're asking me is this the first time I've lived in Texas, the answer is yes.
I had spent a lot of time in Texas, though, during the five years of Continental when we were involved in the pharmaceutical program.
So you knew what the atmosphere was like business-wise?
Yeah, but of course Houston's so different than the rest of the state.
It's probably, I would say that probably Houston is more like Chicago than College Station is like Houston.
Oh, yeah.
both in outlook and in geography.
So when you came, had the funding already been established?
No, the funding was not established then.
In fact, I came here, my first day was September 13, 1982, and the Board of Regents hadn't even approved invent at that time, much to my surprise.
I was going to say, that's a pretty big risk.
Well, I didn't realize I was taking a risk until I got here.
So, were you involved in trying to help get them?
Well, no, Jean Armstrong, well, Skip handled the presentations of the Board of Regents, and to the extent that I gave Skip supporting material, yes, I did help.
But I'm really a neophyte in dealing with the political, political things, as opposed to company political things.
Jane Armstrong has my undying gratitude for having handled it as well as she did.
How did you plunge into this?
Because there was nothing in existence.
Well, yeah, but see, the thing is that when I got here, I knew what I was going to do.
In fact, do you know anything about the hiring procedure they used here?
Okay.
It was a procedure where, first of all, they ran the Adam Wall Street Journal.
They got 125 replies to it.
Then they winnowed it down to, I guess, about 10.
And they had those 10, or whatever number it was, about 10, come down to the campus and have some preliminary interviews.
Then they winnowed that down to three, and they set up a thing that I call the shootout at the A&M Corral.
In industry, when you're being interviewed for a job, it's kept fairly hush-hush, and you never know who the other people are.
Here, they want everybody to stand up in front of God and everybody and give their idea of how they're going to run and vent.
And so they had invited the three finalists,
to meet with faculty, graduate students, honored guests like Kosmetsky and Vick Arnold and those people, and say, what did you do if you were running an event?
This was a new and strange... Did they give you warning before?
Oh yeah, they gave me adequate warning.
It was just that I'd never...
Apparently in academia this is fairly common, but it isn't in business.
And I'll never forget, I had

I had been visiting my daughter in Spain and I got, well first of all I had a hard time sleeping my last night because I was driving back from Cordoba to Madrid and I stopped in Toledo and had a big dinner and lots of coffee and I had trouble falling asleep.
I finally got a couple of hours of sleep and I woke up
at about six in the morning, and I had to drop to Madrid.
Well, six in the morning there is like, I guess, one in the morning in New York.
And drove to Madrid, got on the plane, flew to New York, stood around for three hours in customs, then spent another two hours getting up to Connecticut.
Got home, sat and chatted with my wife for a while.
About midnight New York time.
I said, now I've been awake for 23 hours.
The phone rings, and it's Bill Mules.
And he describes what's going to happen.
I said, Bill, you've got to be kidding me.
But, no, what I did then, after I thought about it for a bit, I figured, well, you know, it's an honest request.
And while the procedure is different than anything I've ever experienced before, I certainly could respond to it.
And what I did was basically lay out a presentation, which I'm almost still using today, explaining what Invent does.
And obviously there have been some changes, but in principle it's been pretty constant.
Could you go through that again?
I can give you a copy of the presentation.
Basically it says that we're going to use faculty and students on a part-time basis.
We're going to organize using two faculty members who will be associate directors.
And they will be responsible for coordinating with the faculty and students so that the faculty, that they're trying to get to work for us, view them as faculty rather than staff.
In fact, it was kind of interesting.
On my first interview, Skip Porter, about 10 o'clock at night, asked me what I thought it would cost to run an event.
And I said, well, gee, I really don't know.
He said, well, we've got another interview at 11 o'clock in the morning.
You and I.
Be prepared to tell me at that time.
I thought, well, okay.
And about 3 o'clock in the morning, I woke up and I thought, well, all right, you know, you can make some assumptions.
You've been doing this work for years, looking at new ideas.
And so I figured, well, all right.
First of all, we'll probably have two or three passes at every idea before we decide whether to go with it or not.
Generally, you get somewhere between two and five percent survival rate of the ideas, depending on how good they are when they come in.
And so I worked out a process that would call for repeated screenings with increasing involvement, so that the first screening would get rid of the trash
Second screening would acquire information.
The third screening would define what it is we had to do and what the cost would be.
And then the fourth thing that we did was to actually implement the plan.
I laid all that out, figured a build-up curve, and came out within, oh, I don't know, 10% of what Skip's estimate was on the dollars.
And I guess he sort of liked that, that he had at least somebody that agreed in spirit with this.
That process was, again, something I'd been following more or less unconsciously in the work I was doing in Continental, because I saw thousands of ideas there.
And I figured, well, if we're going to institutionalize this thing, i.e.
have other people involved with it, we have to give them some idea of what the standards are and what the procedures are and that sort of thing.
And we're still using, in fact, we've got,
That procedure is pretty well locked in now, so we refer to a Stage 1 project or Stage 2, Stage 3, Stage 4.

And also, we're coming fairly close on the percentages, so that the original estimate I made two years ago as to what would survive to go from Stage 1 to Stage 2 to Stage 3 has proven pretty accurate.
We make no attempt to force it and say, well, you've got to eliminate 90%.
It's just, okay, get rid of the garbage on the first pass.
And it turns out it's about 90%, give or take.
And then the idea that we would be active consultants, that we would fill in the gaps in the entrepreneur's ability to put together a business and supply the intellectual resources.
And then also the fact that we would share in the rewards and share in the risks.
So all that was pretty much locked in two years ago.
And it turns out, you know, Jane Armstrong, in putting together the philosophy, had come up with about the same thing.
The whole thing has been beautiful in that there's been a great deal of agreement between myself and Skip and Jane and Harry Whitmore and Bill Muse and Bill Mobley and what have you.
It's everybody moving in the same direction.
And the support I've gotten from those people has just been fabulous.
Just fabulous.
Are Bill Muse and Mobley the vice?
Bill Muse is vice chancellor now, and he was one of the founders of the event, one of the
Theoreticians, I guess.
Bill Mobley is Dean of Business, and he and Bill are both on the Invent Board of Advisors.
We have what amounts to a Board of Directors.

The Board of Directors consists of Bill Mews, Bill Mobley, Jack Kilby, who is an outside consultant, and also the fellow that invented the integrated circuit that makes all computers possible today, Skip, and Jane Armstrong.
You said you wanted two faculty to act as liaisons?
Yeah.
Who are those?
Don Russell from electrical engineering and Ella Van Fleet from business.
And has that helped out from what you see in terms of establishing relationships?
Oh, that's the only way to do it.
First of all, they know all the people well, and they also have an internal evaluation of these folks.
And it would be impossible for me to do the job
coming in from the outside, not knowing anybody.
Just a learning curve would take 10 years.
And they've already experienced all that, and they're working with people that are in their field.
So they've got a real close-up evaluation.
And it's worked out quite well.
In terms of getting the people with the ideas and the new inventions in, how did you go about doing that?
Well, again,
I've been doing this for about 12 years, and my experience has been, and it's been proven again here, getting the people in is not a problem.
It's keeping the door closed enough so they don't get overwhelmed by it.
As soon as the word gets around, you're deluged.
And we've had a great deal of publicity around the state, and every time that an article comes out in some local paper or there's a TV spot or something, it's like a dam break.
So getting ideas in is not a problem.
Getting good ideas is a problem.
But that's true no matter where you are.
First of all, inventors are very persistent people.
Secondly, there are a great deal, a great number of people out there that fancy themselves as being inventors.
They're really conceptualists.
They get an idea and they think that's the end of it.
Now somebody should write them a check and take care of it.
And Edison said that invention is 5% inspiration and 95% perspiration.
Well, we provide the perspiration here.
However, having a good idea isn't enough.
You've got to want to be the one that commercializes it.
And there are very few ideas that we would consider really making a strong investment in that
that don't include the active participation of the inventor, i.e.
the inventor wants to start a business.
And he wants to start the business with this product.
And he's got some ideas for other products, and he's qualified for the business.
And if we can find that, then we get much more excited about even a mediocre product idea than we do about a superb product idea where the guy walks in and says, yeah, OK, now you take care of it.
Because one of the most important ingredients of any business success is a thing called the champion.
And somewhere you have to have a champion.
This is a guy whose entire life is dedicated to making this thing a success.
You can't find champions on staff unless somebody suddenly metamorphizes into it.
And occasionally it does happen, but very infrequently.
Occasionally you'll have somebody walk in from outside that says, hey, look, I run this business and that business on board, and I want to start a new one.
If you have anything, get in touch.
That happens occasionally.
But the champion, you know, it's a big world out there.
There are a lot of forces that work to keep it in the status quo thing.
When you come in with something new, you're changing the status quo.
And this means that you've got to have somebody that is willing to dedicate a very, very significant portion of their waking hours, their energies, and their attention.
And that's what we'd like to see.
And we do have people like that.
The people with the combination?
Yeah, we do have people like that.
Not on our staff, but people coming in.
And those are the ones that really turn us on.
Now, do you work to try and get the people who come in on the street and say, I started this business, this business, do you try and get them together with the others that don't?
Where it's appropriate, we will, yeah.
And in fact, we just sent a team up to Dallas with some concepts looking for manufacturers that might be interested in picking up new products.
So we sort of took the things that we felt were not significant enough to create a business of their own around.
but where somebody that's in a light business might be interested in licensing it.
But this usually doesn't work very well.
This was sort of a last gasp before discarding the things.
And we find that we get things that are, yeah, they're good ideas.
And if somebody's in that business, then maybe they can just pop it in as another product and pay the inventor $100 or something like that.
It might help their business, and it might stimulate some economic activity, which is what we're supposed to be doing.
And those things that are, we call them trivial, if we can package those and find somebody that wants a few new products.
And they're usually anomaly items of one sort or another.
Now, we do have one.
In fact, it was the first business that we started.
It's a board game called Aggie Days.
And it's sort of a monopoly game.
Not quite, but it uses squares and you move things.
And all the squares, well, I don't know if it's in the stores yet, are related to Texas A&M.
And we see the market as being the students, but more likely the parents of students and the former students.
Yeah, somebody to give it to the kids for Christmas and that sort of thing.
And then the former students who want a little trip and nostalgia.
This was brought to us by a student, a guy named John Ward.
And John has already started several businesses.
He's got a flying school.
And he had developed a knee pad for aviators for keeping notes.
And he sold some 2,000 of those.
And we thought the board game had some very interesting aspects to it, as did John Ward himself.
John is a real driver.
And we felt that, number one, he probably was going to go ahead and do the business whether we were involved or not.
So he'd be better off if we were involved.
Secondly, where he would run out of steam, we thought, was in picking up what he learned and then proliferating it to other campuses.
And so we're putting together a strategy for him, watching what's happening here and then identifying target campuses for the next move and a methodology
or handling it on other campuses.
So like the UT board game?
Yeah, right.
And of course, this would be probably most successful on those campuses with a high degree of nostalgia.
Somehow, I think the Chicago campus of the University of Illinois would not attract too many old alums.
But OU and UT?
Yeah, yeah.
And certainly, if it's not a success here, there's no chance it's going to be a success any place.

But John was up and running about a month ago, and he, one of the things he was going to have was to sell advertising space on the game board, and apparently he's already got $6,000 in advertising revenues out of some of the local businesses.
And these are all nostalgia type places around here, so.
We looked to that one to be a small, but a successful business.
And then the second one,
that I consider done, it's actually moving into its final stages of financing now, is a local businessman who had been producing some power packs for photo flash units.
Yeah, and he came to us and asked for some help, so we're giving it to him.
Now he's, as I say, in the final stages of signing the contract for the financing, and he'll be off and running.
did some in-depth market surveys for them, and they got some strategies, and helped them negotiate with the sources of capital so they wouldn't take too much of the business away from them.
I look to that one as being a success too.
Again, this is connected to a guy that's already in business, starting a new business, and with a great deal of drive and creativity.
So those are the ones that will have
the highest probability of success.
How does this, being in a public university, how does it differ from organizations that do the same type of thing privately?
Well, I think first of all, we're not in it for the money.
We do take a piece of the action, and this means that if the business is an outstanding success, we're making an outstanding amount of money in our investment.
We don't take any money upfront though, nor do we take any debt of any sort.
So, the things that do it, first of all, there's quote, invention marketing companies.
My experience in viewing their reports has been that they use good paper and
they have maybe one or two pages that are germane to that particular product, and a lot of boilerplate.
And they charge $1,500 to $1,800 for that.
They usually propose then that they will, for another $3,000 or $4,000, they will expose this invention to 500 manufacturers and that sort of thing.
Generally, the people have,
that have used those services has come to us after the first report, and they're very dissatisfied with what they spent their money on.
There are commercial venture capital companies, but we get involved before a venture capital company would be interested.
In fact, our output is something that the venture capital company would need in order to decide whether or not to make an investment.
Also, we don't take the same proportion of the business that the venture capital company would demand.
We're also able to take things that are smaller and that never will be astoundingly large, because our main goal is the creation of businesses, not making a lot of money for our investors.
So we take higher risk things.
We take things that probably would not have another avenue.
And we take things that probably will never be very large, or that can never be very large, simply because the market may not be all that big.
But we'd like to see something that, if we had a rule of thumb, we'd say, well, maybe in five years they'll do $5 million in sales.
Venture capital companies would like to see them do $100 million in five years.
And they'll screen out anything that doesn't have that
potential, at least, realizing that the potential is very seldom met, and that's where their risk comes in.
But venture capital companies are in it for the buck, as are their investors, and they tend to place more of their money as growth capital for businesses that are always running.
So you may have a company that is now in the upswing of its growth curve,
and needs some money to finance its growth.
It's run out of bankable loans and isn't quite positioned yet to sell its stock publicly.
So venture capitalists will help out there.
And that's where the venture capitalists are making a lot of their investments.
We don't even get involved with that.
So that's, I guess, how we differ.
Also, we have the faculty available to us
But there are other companies, other venture capital companies that use nearby universities as sources of talent, and they hire the professors on a consultant basis.
And they may actually have an easier job than we do, because we can't pay a professor to work overtime for us, because we've got state funds.
He's already working 100% for the state, so he can't have him working 110% for the state.
And what we do...
is provide release time for teaching.
So, we say, well, fine, we'll pay a third of your salary and you only have to teach two-thirds of the classes.
Generally, that last third doesn't really require that much more work because he's teaching the same class a third time, that's all.
And so, our providing
a third of his salary in exchange for him working for us thirteen hours a week isn't all that attractive, and so we have some problems getting faculty members there.
What about publications?
And of course, that's a big problem.
That's a big problem.
So far, there's been one publication that has come out of people working for a guy.
What was it?
It had to do with industrial marketing, a project we're working on with a water cleanup
This will be running in a magazine called Industrial Marketing this summer by Al Bush and George Lucas.
But generally, we don't do the kind of work that you could consider research.
We're trying to build something and make it work.
We're not trying to discover any new principles.
The market research that we do is, I think, very interesting to the participants.
I know they're having a ball because they're getting out in the real world and seeing how it is.
I think that from that standpoint, they're learning an awful lot, but again, that doesn't come to a publication.
I talked to Pustay in the business, and he said that part of the way they're trying to handle it is getting more towards a graduate program.
Yeah, well, they would invent a couple of other projects they're having trouble with that aren't what he calls a win-win situation for them.
Yeah.
And have you found a good record with using graduate students?
Yeah.
In fact, this game business was done entirely by graduate students, and it amazed me because
After they had done the first two phases of evaluation, they said, do you want to go ahead with it?
I said, sure, go ahead, do phase three, which is lay out the plan, tell me what you're going to do.
Well, what they did was go ahead and did it.
And the next time they touched base with me, the business plan had been completed, and the business was ready to get started.
And I thought, you know, there should be more people like that here.
But we're using more graduate student time now than faculty time.
And ideally...
I think we should fall back to a position where the faculty provides supervision and advice and doesn't do any of the actual work.

Trouble is that, again, it's simply a matter of years and presumably the faculty has more experience than the graduate students and they're able to interpret better what they're hearing than the graduate students.
Graduate students will take things
And the faculty members, particularly as they've been out in business, have seen a couple of things like this before, and they weren't quite what they seemed to be.
So they can put some English on what they're hearing.
I haven't talked to anyone in the engineering department about the event.
Are you having similar problems with engineering in terms of the publication?
I think it's a greater problem with engineering than with business.
They're testing for you, essentially, right?
Well, no, they're analyzing neurons.
We've got a rather heavy development program in one plastic device, and we've got a faculty member working half-time all year round on that particular project.
But I would say that we have more problems in engineering, simply because in engineering,
most engineers can sell all their available consulting time.
And if they're going to take time out from publications and teaching, they can get paid more, and it's extra money in their pocket, by just picking up a consulting contract and working on that.
And they get in six days what we'll pay them in the semester for working part-time for us.
Are these problems things that you realize you would run up against?
No, no.
Because it's a totally different world.
That part of it, yeah.
I would say to some extent, too, I'm maybe a little surprised by how self-centered some of the faculty appears to be at times.
And maybe I shouldn't be.
Somehow I thought that in an educational institution that there would be a
maybe more charity, and I find out it's maybe the same or maybe less than you find it in business.
But everybody's the same?
Well, I guess that's what it amounts to, right.
Who do you deal with in the university system?
Do you deal with anyone outside of teams?
Well, the College of Business, yeah, and rather extensively there.
We do have some dealings with the School of Medicine.
We have initiated some dealings with UT Arlington, HARC, and we're trying to set up a project at UT Austin.
And since we are a state organization,
perfectly justified in doing that.
In fact, it's recommended that we do.
Now, this is one particular project you're working on, or a totally separate, affiliated in-vent project?

Well, it would be an individual project that would be worked on there rather than here, mainly because the inventor's in Austin, and UT Austin has some people that are particularly talented in this particular field.
and it would just make a great deal of sense to do it out there.
And that's in the process of it, so.
Now, were you involved at all in the setting up of the UTR and the T-Center, or did you take advantage of most of the center?
You're talking about the Small Business Development Company Center, SBDC, Small Business Development Center.
To the extent that I met with John Rouse up there and told him what we were doing here,
and had some preliminary discussions with some of his people, offered our services.
Occasionally he sends somebody down here to talk to us, and he thinks that they need our help more than his, and that sort of thing.
And I send people up there when I think that they need his help more than ours.
So from that standpoint, I was not directly involved in setting it up.
Harry Whitmore, I guess, had handled that.
Harry had skipped it in there.
to the extent that there was a transfer of information, yeah, it wasn't local.
Could he deal with inside the system?
Inside the A&M system?
Yeah.
All right.
Inside the A&M system, again, it's College of Business, TEAS, any other college dean that we need.
Bill Mews, Mark Money, I guess indirectly through Perry Atkinson.
I've had some dealings with agriculture with the Ag Experiment Station.
Other than that, no.
It's mostly business and engineering.
Outside, too, by the way, the sources of capital, venture capitalists, that sort of commercial world.
You do try and get them together with the capital.
Yeah, when it's advisable.
Once you've gotten past that stage.
Yeah, right now, we don't have anything big enough to go to venture capital with.
We've used local financing on that.
But when you get up toward the million mark,
and you really get your act put together, then you can go and watch a cat bus.
But you have helped them get together with local planners?
Yeah.
What do you do as, you know, you've got whole organizations that I put, do you as director of this, of this invent, what stages do you get into?
I don't know, inspire a lead, put out fires.
I see my role as being the interface with the outside.
and a policy role, and a supervisory role over procedures, and particularly the stage four programs.
And for instance, right now I'm missing our Wednesday morning staff meeting, which is not a staff meeting per se, but it's a stage four review meeting.

Now, what we do is when a program gets to this implementation stage where we're actually doing product development and actually running the business part and actually sending out market researchers, we appoint a faculty member as team leader.
And he basically puts together a little company.
He's got some marketing people, and he's got some finance people, and he's got some engineering people.
He's got some strategy people.
He may play several of these roles himself.
But whatever he needs, we try to get for him in the way of talent.
It's his job, then, to try to keep the thing on track, try to hit the schedule objectives, milestones, and bring the program in.
So once a week, we spend a half hour per program in which he reports what's going on, what his problems are, what help he needs.
And this meeting is just the team leader, the two associate directors, and myself.
And we've set up a procedure where when the half hour is up, that's the end of that meter.
If we have to meet more on that, we reschedule that particular month.
This way, you don't wind up with some projects being cheated and others getting too much attention.
I meet with the inventors frequently.
And I like to get involved myself with them.
Oh, particularly ones in which I feel particularly competent.
Power generation, thermodynamics, things that I may have been involved in in the past.
In industry, I think I'm going to bring some insight in on these things.
So I like to get my hands dirty on those.
But to come up with a job description, that's difficult.
I think it's difficult in the whole organization.
Yeah, it really is.
I think if you can't, that's why they have such nice titles.
You know, you're vice president of sales.
Everybody knows what that is, so you don't have to explain it to them.
But I guess, you know, to the extent that I'm the president of the company here, reporting to my board of directors, and fairly autonomous.
So from that standpoint, it's very satisfying.
And I've been satisfied with the results.
A little anxious that they
We stopped popping things out faster, but it just took longer to get them through the pipeline than I thought they would.
In terms of flexibility, are you as flexible here as you were in the private sector?
Yes and no.
I think that, well, let's put it this way.
It's harder to do things.
You don't have as much money available.
Because people are locked into semester schedules that are scheduled a year and a half in advance, they're not always available.
And in a company, it was always possible to get ahold of somebody for some length of time.
I remember talking to one of my former Continental Group associates.
And he said, what kind of funding do you have for this operation?
I said, well, we've got a million dollars for the biennium.
So that's a half million dollars a year.
They said, Frank, that used to be your expense account.
So from the standpoint of money, in the standpoint of being able to go outside and get help, we try very hard to use the help internally.
As a result, it slows things down.
Recently, we did have to go outside.
And gee, just the procedures of getting
an outside consultant, I get with the governor, they're okay.
Amazing.
I guess approval levels, yeah, there's also approval.
We had a letter come through here the other day requesting permission for, well, AINVENT was going to fund the presentation of a paper in France, and this was because of some work that had been done.
it turned out that it looked like it required 19 approvals.

You know, it started out with the guy requesting it, went through his assistant department head, his department head, went through his assistant dean, his dean, came over to T's, went through Skip, went through me, then was going to head on up through Vanderveer and Hanson, and ultimately, I don't know, through two state senators and the governor or something.
I couldn't believe it.
Do you...
